<h1 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Factors and Multiples in Whole Numbers</h1>
</div>

<article>
<p>
A <strong>factor</strong> is simply a number that can divide another whole number without any remainder e.g. 16/<b>2</b> = 8, 16/<b>4</b> = 4 and 16/<b>8</b> = 2. Then we can say <b>2</b>, <b>4</b> and <b>8</b> are factors of 16.
<br>
The whole numbers; 1, 2, 4, 8 and 16 all divide into 16 can be regarded as <b>factors</b> of 16.
<br>
<strong class='text-primary'>Note: 1 is a common factor of all whole numbers </strong>i.e. 1 can divide all whole numbers.
</p>
</article>

<article>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>How to Determine Factors of a Whole Number.</h2>
</div>

<p>
i.	Break the whole number down into its component numbers.
<br>
ii.	Find all the possible products of the component numbers that can divide the whole number without any remainder.
<br>
iii.	Write out all the products including <b> 1</b>.
</p>
<p>
<strong class='text-danger'>Note: Product means multiplying two or more numbers together.</strong>
</p>

<b>Example 1</b>
<br>
(i) Find all the factors of 28.
<br>
(ii) Find all the factors of 32.
<br>
<b>Solution(i)</b>
<br>
<b>28</b> = 1 x 2 x 2 x 7
<br>
Possible Products => 1 x 2 = <b>2</b>, 2 x 2 = <b>4</b>, 1 x 7 = <b>7</b>, 2 x 7 = <b>14</b> and 2 x 14 = <b>28</b>.
<br>
<b>Factors</b> are => <b>1, 2, 4, 7, 14 and 28</b>.
<br>
<b>Solution(ii)</b>
<br>
<b>32</b> = 1 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 2
<br>
Possible Products => 1 x 2 = <b>2</b>, 2 x 2 = <b>4</b>, 4 x 2 = <b>8</b>, 8 x 2 = <b>16</b>, 16 x 2 =<b>32</b>.
<br>
<strong>Factors</strong> are => <strong>1, 2, 4, 8, 16 and 32</strong>.
</article>

<article>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Prime Numbers.</h3>
</div>
<p>
A prime number is a number divisible only by 1 and itself i.e. it has only two factors; itself and 1 e.g. Prime numbers between 1---20 are; 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17 and 19. <strong>Note: 1 is not a prime number</strong>.
</p>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h4 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Prime Factors</h4>
</div>
<p>
<strong>Prime factors</strong> of a number are factors of that number that are prime numbers obtained by breaking the number down into its component prime numbers.
<br>
<b>Example 1</b>
<br>
Find the prime factors of 24.
<br>
<b>Solution</b>
<br>
<b>24</b> = 2 x 2 x 2 x 3 (<strong>Prime Factors</strong>)
</p>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h4 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Rules for Finding Prime Factors of a Number</h4>
</div>
<p>
(i)	Begin with the lowest prime number, 2 and check if it will divide the number, if not use the next prime number, 3, then move on to try 5, 7, 11 and so on.
<br>
(ii)	If a prime number can divide the number, confirm if it will divide the result again before moving to the next prime number.
<br>
<b>Example 1</b>
<br>
Express 72 as a product of its prime actors.
<br>
<b>Solution</b>
<br>
2 => 72
<br>
2 => 36
<br>
2 => 18
<br>
3 => 9
<br>
3 => 3
<br>
