<br>
72 = <strong>2 x 2 x 2 x 3 x 3</strong>
</p>
 
<p>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h2 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Prime Factors in the Index Form</h2>
</div>

<strong>Index form</strong> is the writing of a number in its raise to power form e.g. 
16 = 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 = 2<sup>4</sup> , then 4 in 2<sup>4</sup>  is the <b>power</b> or <b>index</b>. Therefore, 
the power of <b>2</b> is called <strong>Squared</strong> and the power of <b>3</b> is called <strong>Cubed</strong> i.e.  
3<sup>2</sup> => three squared, 2<sup>3</sup> => two cubed.
<br>
<b>Example 1</b>
<br>
Express each of 48, 92 and 675 as a product of the prime factors. Leave your answer in the index form.
<br>
<b>Solution</b>
<br>
48 = 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 3 => 2<sup>4</sup> x 3 (<strong>index form</strong>)
<br>
92 = 2 x 2 x 23 => 2<sup>2</sup> X 23 (<strong>index form</strong>)
<br>
675 = 3 x 3 x 3 x 5 x 5 => 3<sup>3</sup> x 5<sup>2</sup> (<strong>index form</strong>)
</p>
</article>

<article>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Common Factors</h3>
</div>

<p>
A factor of more than one number is called a <strong>common factor</strong> e.g. 10 and 14 are divisible by 2, then 2 is a common factor of 10 and 14.
</p>
<p>
If a set of numbers have more than one <strong>common factor</strong>, the product of the factors will be the <b>common factor </b>of that set of numbers e.g. 21, 35 and 56 are divisible by 3 and 7, then the <strong>common factor</strong> is 3 x 7 => <strong>21.</strong>
</p>

<p>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>HCF (Highest Common Factor)</h3>
</div>

<strong>HCF </strong>is the biggest number that will divide two or more numbers.
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>How to Determine the HCF of a Set of Numbers</h3>
</div>
i.	Express the numbers as a product of the prime factors.
<br>
ii. Identify all the common prime factors.
<br>
iii. Find the product of the common prime factors to get the HCF.
<br>
<b>Example 1</b>
<br>
Find the HCF of 24, 40 and 64.
<br>
<b>Solution</b>
<br>
24 = (2) x (2) x (2) x 3 
<br>
40 = (2) x (2) x (2) x 5 
<br>
64 = (2) x (2) x (2) x 2 x 2 x 2
<br>
HCF = 2 x 2 x 2 => <b>8</b> (i.e. 2 is common to the three numbers 3 times)

<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Using Index Notation</h3>
</div>
<b>Example 2</b>
<br>
Find the HCF of 144, 216 and 360 using index notation
<br>
<b>Solution</b>
<br>
144 = 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 3 x 3 => 2<sup>4</sup> x 3<sup>2</sup>
<br>
216 = 2 x 2 x 2 x 3 x 3 x 3 => 2<sup>3</sup> x 3<sup>3</sup> 
<br>
360 = 2 x 2 x 2 x 3 x 3 x 5 => 2<sup>3</sup> x 3<sup>2</sup> x 5
<br>
In the above, the lowest power of 2 is 3 and the lowest power of 3 is 2. Then we need to rewrite the index notation of the numbers according to the lowest powers of the prime factors.
<br>
144 = (2<sup>3</sup> x 3<sup>2</sup>) x 2
<br>
216 = (2<sup>3</sup>x 3<sup>2</sup>) x 3
<br>
360 = (2<sup>3</sup> x 3<sup>2</sup>) x 5
<br>
2<sup>3</sup>and 3<sup>2</sup> are common to all the numbers. Therefore, <strong>HCF</strong> = 2<sup>3</sup> x 3<sup>2</sup> = 8 x 9 => <b>72</b>
</p>

<p>
<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Multiples</h3>
</div>

<strong>Multiples</strong> are set of numbers that can be divided by a particular whole number. A <strong>multiple</strong> is the product of factors e.g. 6, 9, 12, 15 are <strong>multiples of 3</strong>.


<div class="d-flex justify-content-center mt-3">
<h3 class='text-dark justify-content-center'>Common Multiples</h3>
</div>


<b>Multiple of 3</b> => 6, 9, <b>12</b>, 15, 18, 21, 24, 27, 30
<br>
<b>Multiple of 6 </b> => <b>12</b>, 18, 24, 30
<br>
<b>12</b> is a <b>common multiple </b>of 3 and 6. 
<br>
Other <b>common multiples</b> of 3 and 6 => <b>18</b>, <b>24</b> and <b>30</b>
<br>

<div class="container">
  <div class="row">
    <div class="col border-right border-danger">
    <b>Example 1</b>
    <br>
    Find five multiples of 2 and 5.
    <br>
    <b>Solution</b>
    <br>
    Multiples of 2 => <b>4, 6, 8, 10, 12</b>
    <br>
    Multiples of 5 => <b>10, 15, 20, 25, 30</b>
   </div>
